[49m[39m    1,   1[0m:[39m[49m # Recipe 6.1: Geographic Patient Clustering ⭐
[0m[49m[39m    2,   2[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m    3,   3[0m:[39m[49m **Complexity:** Simple · **Phase:** MVP · **Estimated Cost:** ~$0.10 per 10,000 patients clustered
[0m[49m[39m    4,   4[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m    5,   5[0m:[39m[49m ---
[0m[49m[39m    6,   6[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m    7,   7[0m:[39m[49m ## The Problem
[0m[49m[39m    8,   8[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m    9,   9[0m:[39m[49m A regional health system with 14 clinics is trying to decide where to open clinic number 15. They have 200,000 patients in their EHR. They know where those patients live (addresses on file). They know which clinic each patient currently visits. But they don't know where the gaps are. They don't know which ZIP codes have patients driving 45 minutes past a closer competitor because there's nothing in between. They don't know which neighborhoods are growing, which are aging, and which are losing population to the suburbs.
[0m[49m[39m   10,  10[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   11,  11[0m:[39m[49m This isn't a hypothetical. Every health system with more than a handful of locations faces this question constantly: where are our patients, where should we be, and where are we losing people to distance?
[0m[49m[39m   12,  12[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   13,  13[0m:[39m[49m The same geographic clustering problem shows up in community health assessment (which neighborhoods have the worst outcomes and the fewest resources?), mobile health unit routing (where should the van go on Tuesdays?), pandemic response (which areas need testing sites?), and network adequacy reporting (can we prove to CMS that 90% of our members live within 15 miles of a provider?).
[0m[49m[39m   14,  14[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   15,  15[0m:[39m[49m The data is sitting right there in the EHR: patient addresses, visit histories, diagnoses. The challenge isn't getting the data. It's turning 200,000 individual addresses into actionable geographic intelligence that a VP of Strategy can use to make a $40 million facility decision.
[0m[49m[39m   16,  16[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   17,  17[0m:[39m[49m Here's how you turn 200,000 addresses into something a VP of Strategy can actually use.
[0m[49m[39m   18,  18[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   19,  19[0m:[39m[49m ---
[0m[49m[39m   20,  20[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   21,  21[0m:[39m[49m ## The Technology: Spatial Clustering from First Principles
[0m[49m[39m   22,  22[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   23,  23[0m:[39m[49m ### What Is Geographic Clustering?
[0m[49m[39m   24,  24[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   25,  25[0m:[39m[49m At its core, geographic clustering is the process of grouping points on a map into meaningful regions based on proximity and density. You have a set of coordinates (latitude/longitude pairs derived from patient addresses), and you want to find natural groupings: areas where patients concentrate, gaps where they don't, and boundaries that make operational sense.
[0m[49m[39m   26,  26[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   27,  27[0m:[39m[49m This sounds trivial. Plot the dots, draw circles around the dense areas, done. In practice, it's more nuanced than that, because "meaningful" depends entirely on what you're trying to do. A cluster that makes sense for facility planning (where should we build?) looks different from one that makes sense for community health (which neighborhoods share risk factors?), which looks different from one that makes sense for network adequacy (can we prove geographic coverage?).
[0m[49m[39m   28,  28[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   29,  29[0m:[39m[49m ### The Classic Algorithms
[0m[49m[39m   30,  30[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   31,  31[0m:[39m[49m **K-Means** is the algorithm most people learn first. You pick K (the number of clusters you want), and the algorithm iteratively assigns each point to its nearest cluster center, then moves the centers to the middle of their assigned points. Repeat until stable. It's fast, intuitive, and works well when your clusters are roughly spherical and roughly the same size.
[0m[49m[39m   32,  32[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   33,  33[0m:[39m[49m The problem with K-Means for geographic data: you have to pick K in advance. How many clusters should 200,000 patients form? 10? 50? 200? The answer depends on your use case, and K-Means gives you no guidance. It also assumes clusters are convex (roughly circular), which geographic populations rarely are. People cluster along highways, around town centers, in irregular suburban sprawl patterns.
[0m[49m[39m   34,  34[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   35,  35[0m:[39m[49m **DBSCAN** (Density-Based Spatial Clustering of Applications with Noise) takes a different approach. Instead of pre-specifying the number of clusters, you specify two parameters: epsilon (how close points need to be to count as neighbors) and min_samples (how many neighbors a point needs to be considered part of a dense region). DBSCAN finds clusters of arbitrary shape, handles noise (isolated points that don't belong to any cluster), and doesn't require you to guess the number of clusters in advance.
[0m[49m[39m   36,  36[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   37,  37[0m:[39m[49m For geographic patient data, DBSCAN is often the better starting point. Patient populations don't form neat circles. They form irregular blobs along transit corridors, around commercial centers, and in residential developments. DBSCAN respects that reality.
[0m[49m[39m   38,  38[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   39,  39[0m:[39m[49m **HDBSCAN** (Hierarchical DBSCAN) extends DBSCAN by varying the density threshold and building a hierarchy of clusters. It handles populations with varying density (dense urban core, sparse rural fringe) better than plain DBSCAN, which uses a single density threshold everywhere. If your service area spans both downtown and farmland, HDBSCAN is worth the extra complexity.
[0m[49m[39m   40,  40[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   41,  41[0m:[39m[49m ### Geocoding: The Unglamorous Foundation
[0m[49m[39m   42,  42[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   43,  43[0m:[39m[49m Before you can cluster anything, you need coordinates. Patient records have addresses. Addresses are text strings. Clustering algorithms need numbers (latitude, longitude). The process of converting "123 Main St, Springfield, IL 62701" into (39.7817, -89.6501) is called geocoding.
[0m[49m[39m   44,  44[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   45,  45[0m:[39m[49m Geocoding sounds like a solved problem. It mostly is, for well-formed US addresses. But healthcare data is messy:
[0m[49m[39m   46,  46[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   47,  47[0m:[39m[49m - PO Boxes don't have a meaningful geographic location (they represent a post office, not where the patient lives)
[0m[49m[39m   48,  48[0m:[39m[49m - Homeless patients may have a shelter address, a last-known address, or no address at all
[0m[49m[39m   49,  49[0m:[39m[49m - Rural addresses sometimes use route-and-box notation that geocoders struggle with
[0m[49m[39m   50,  50[0m:[39m[49m - Apartment numbers don't affect coordinates but do affect density calculations
[0m[49m[39m   51,  51[0m:[39m[49m - Patients move. The address in the EHR might be six months stale.
[0m[49m[39m   52,  52[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   53,  53[0m:[39m[49m A geocoding step that silently drops 15% of your patients (the ones with PO Boxes, bad addresses, or missing data) will bias your clusters toward populations with stable housing and well-formed addresses. That's exactly the population you probably don't need to worry about. The patients you're missing are often the ones who need geographic access the most.
[0m[49m[39m   54,  54[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   55,  55[0m:[39m[49m ### Distance Metrics: Not All Miles Are Equal
[0m[49m[39m   56,  56[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   57,  57[0m:[39m[49m When clustering geographic points, the obvious distance metric is "as the crow flies" (Haversine distance between two lat/long pairs). But patients don't fly. They drive. Or take the bus. Or walk.
[0m[49m[39m   58,  58[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   59,  59[0m:[39m[49m A patient who lives 3 miles from a clinic but across a river with no bridge is functionally farther away than a patient who lives 8 miles away on a straight highway. Drive-time isochrones (the area reachable within X minutes of driving) are more meaningful than radius circles for healthcare access analysis.
[0m[49m[39m   60,  60[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   61,  61[0m:[39m[49m For initial clustering, Haversine distance is fine. It's fast, requires no external API calls, and gives you directionally correct results. But when you're making facility placement decisions, you'll want to validate clusters against actual drive times. A cluster of 5,000 patients that looks compact on a map might actually span a 45-minute drive if there's a mountain or a river in the middle.
[0m[49m[39m   62,  62[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   63,  63[0m:[39m[49m ### What Makes Healthcare Geographic Clustering Different
[0m[49m[39m   64,  64[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   65,  65[0m:[39m[49m Generic geographic clustering (where should we put a Starbucks?) differs from healthcare geographic clustering in a few important ways:
[0m[49m[39m   66,  66[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   67,  67[0m:[39m[49m **Regulatory requirements.** CMS network adequacy standards specify maximum distance and drive-time thresholds by specialty type. Your clusters need to map to these thresholds, not arbitrary boundaries. For Medicare Advantage plans, 90% of urban members must live within specific distances of specific provider types. Your clustering needs to prove (or disprove) compliance.
[0m[49m[39m   68,  68[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   69,  69[0m:[39m[49m **Equity considerations.** If your clusters reveal that underserved populations are systematically farther from care, that's not just a business insight. It's a health equity finding with regulatory, reputational, and moral implications. Geographic clustering in healthcare is never purely operational.
[0m[49m[39m   70,  70[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   71,  71[0m:[39m[49m **PHI sensitivity.** Patient addresses are PHI. The coordinates derived from them are PHI. The clusters themselves, if small enough to be re-identified, are PHI. You can't just dump 200,000 lat/long pairs into a public mapping tool. The entire pipeline needs to operate within your HIPAA boundary.
[0m[49m[39m   72,  72[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   73,  73[0m:[39m[49m **Temporal dynamics.** Patient populations shift. New housing developments, highway construction, employer relocations, seasonal residents. A clustering analysis from January may not reflect reality in July. Build for refresh, not one-shot analysis.
[0m[49m[39m   74,  74[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   75,  75[0m:[39m[49m ### The General Architecture Pattern
[0m[49m[39m   76,  76[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   77,  77[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m   78,  78[0m:[39m[49m [Address Data] → [Geocode] → [Clean/Filter] → [Cluster] → [Enrich] → [Visualize/Analyze]
[0m[49m[39m   79,  79[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m   80,  80[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   81,  81[0m:[39m[49m **Address Data.** Extract patient addresses from your source system (EHR, claims, enrollment). Include visit history and demographics if you want to enrich clusters later.
[0m[49m[39m   82,  82[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   83,  83[0m:[39m[49m **Geocode.** Convert addresses to latitude/longitude coordinates. Handle failures gracefully (PO Boxes, invalid addresses, missing data). Log what you couldn't geocode so you know your coverage gaps.
[0m[49m[39m   84,  84[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   85,  85[0m:[39m[49m **Clean/Filter.** Remove duplicates (same patient, same address counted once). Handle edge cases (coordinates at 0,0 mean geocoding failed, not that your patient lives in the Gulf of Guinea). Apply any geographic bounding box (exclude patients outside your service area).
[0m[49m[39m   86,  86[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   87,  87[0m:[39m[49m **Cluster.** Apply your chosen algorithm. For most healthcare use cases, start with DBSCAN or HDBSCAN. Tune parameters based on your operational question: tight clusters for facility micro-siting, loose clusters for regional planning.
[0m[49m[39m   88,  88[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   89,  89[0m:[39m[49m **Enrich.** Attach metadata to each cluster: patient count, average age, payer mix, top diagnoses, utilization patterns. A cluster is just a set of coordinates until you attach meaning to it.
[0m[49m[39m   90,  90[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   91,  91[0m:[39m[49m **Visualize/Analyze.** Render clusters on a map. Calculate summary statistics. Compare against existing facility locations, competitor locations, and regulatory thresholds. Generate the artifacts that decision-makers need.
[0m[49m[39m   92,  92[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   93,  93[0m:[39m[49m ---
[0m[49m[39m   94,  94[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   95,  95[0m:[39m[49m ## The AWS Implementation
[0m[49m[39m   96,  96[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   97,  97[0m:[39m[49m ### Why These Services
[0m[49m[39m   98,  98[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   99,  99[0m:[39m[49m **Amazon Location Service for geocoding.** Location Service provides a managed geocoding API that converts addresses to coordinates without requiring you to run your own geocoding infrastructure. It supports high-throughput geocoding (important when you're processing 200,000 addresses), returns confidence scores, and operates within the AWS compliance boundary. Before sending patient addresses to Location Service, verify that it appears on the current [AWS HIPAA Eligible Services list](https://aws.amazon.com/compliance/hipaa-eligible-services-reference/). The eligible services list is updated periodically; check at implementation time. If Location Service is not listed when you implement, geocode using a self-hosted solution (e.g., Pelias or Nominatim on EC2 within your VPC) or use a geocoding provider with whom you have a BAA.
[0m[49m[39m  100, 100[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  101, 101[0m:[39m[49m **Amazon S3 for data storage.** Patient address extracts, geocoded coordinates, and cluster results all need durable, encrypted storage. S3 with SSE-KMS provides the encryption at rest, and S3's integration with every other AWS service makes it the natural data lake layer.
[0m[49m[39m  102, 102[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  103, 103[0m:[39m[49m **AWS Lambda for orchestration and clustering logic.** The geocoding and clustering steps are batch workloads that run periodically (weekly or monthly refresh). Lambda handles the orchestration: trigger the geocoding batch, run the clustering algorithm, write results. For datasets under ~500,000 points, the clustering algorithm itself runs comfortably within Lambda's memory and timeout limits.
[0m[49m[39m  104, 104[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  105, 105[0m:[39m[49m <!-- TODO (TechWriter): Expert review ARCH-1 (MEDIUM). Add note recommending Step Functions Map state for orchestrating geocoding batches over 50K addresses to avoid Lambda timeout risk. -->
[0m[49m[39m  106, 106[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  107, 107[0m:[39m[49m **Amazon SageMaker for large-scale clustering.** If your patient population exceeds what Lambda can handle in memory (roughly 500K+ points with enrichment data), SageMaker provides managed compute for running scikit-learn or custom clustering jobs. SageMaker Processing Jobs give you ephemeral compute that spins up, runs the algorithm, writes results to S3, and shuts down. For datasets exceeding 500K points or requiring GPU-accelerated HDBSCAN, replace the clustering Lambda with a SageMaker Processing Job. The job reads from the same S3 geocoded/ prefix, runs the same algorithm, and writes to the same cluster-results/ prefix. The only difference is compute: SageMaker provides instances with more memory and optional GPU. Use the `sklearn` container or bring your own.
[0m[49m[39m  108, 108[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  109, 109[0m:[39m[49m **Amazon QuickSight for visualization.** QuickSight supports geospatial visualizations (point maps, filled maps, heat maps) and connects directly to S3 or Athena. For the "show me where the clusters are" question that executives ask, QuickSight delivers without requiring a custom mapping application.
[0m[49m[39m  110, 110[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  111, 111[0m:[39m[49m **Amazon DynamoDB for cluster metadata.** Once clusters are computed, downstream systems need fast lookups: "which cluster does this patient belong to?" or "what are the characteristics of cluster 7?" DynamoDB provides single-digit-millisecond reads for these access patterns. Restrict DynamoDB access to the cluster-results tables using IAM policies scoped to specific roles (the pipeline write role and the dashboard read role). Use an opaque patient identifier (not MRN) as the partition key; maintain the MRN mapping in a separate, more tightly controlled identity service. The patient-clusters table contains home location data for your entire active population; treat it as a high-sensitivity asset.
[0m[49m[39m  112, 112[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  113, 113[0m:[39m[49m ### Architecture Diagram
[0m[49m[39m  114, 114[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  115, 115[0m:[39m[49m ```mermaid
[0m[49m[39m  116, 116[0m:[39m[49m flowchart TD
[0m[49m[39m  117, 117[0m:[39m[49m     A[EHR / Enrollment System] -->|Address Extract| B[S3 Bucket\nraw-addresses/]
[0m[49m[39m  118, 118[0m:[39m[49m     B -->|Batch Trigger| C[Lambda\ngeocoder]
[0m[49m[39m  119, 119[0m:[39m[49m     C -->|Per-Address Geocode| D[Amazon Location Service]
[0m[49m[39m  120, 120[0m:[39m[49m     D -->|Coordinates| C
[0m[49m[39m  121, 121[0m:[39m[49m     C -->|Write| E[S3 Bucket\ngeocoded/]
[0m[49m[39m  122, 122[0m:[39m[49m     E -->|Trigger| F[Lambda or SageMaker\nclustering-engine]
[0m[49m[39m  123, 123[0m:[39m[49m     F -->|DBSCAN / HDBSCAN| F
[0m[49m[39m  124, 124[0m:[39m[49m     F -->|Write| G[S3 Bucket\ncluster-results/]
[0m[49m[39m  125, 125[0m:[39m[49m     G --> H[DynamoDB\ncluster-metadata]
[0m[49m[39m  126, 126[0m:[39m[49m     G --> I[QuickSight\nGeospatial Dashboard]
[0m[49m[39m  127, 127[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  128, 128[0m:[39m[49m     style D fill:#ff9,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[39m  129, 129[0m:[39m[49m     style F fill:#f9f,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[39m  130, 130[0m:[39m[49m     style I fill:#9ff,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[39m  131, 131[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  132, 132[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  133, 133[0m:[39m[49m ### Prerequisites
[0m[49m[39m  134, 134[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  135, 135[0m:[39m[49m | Requirement | Details |
[0m[49m[39m  136, 136[0m:[39m[49m |-------------|---------|
[0m[49m[39m  137, 137[0m:[39m[49m | **AWS Services** | Amazon Location Service, Amazon S3, AWS Lambda, Amazon DynamoDB, Amazon QuickSight (optional), Amazon SageMaker (for large datasets) |
[0m[49m[39m  138, 138[0m:[39m[49m | **IAM Permissions** | Geocoding Lambda: `geo:SearchPlaceIndexForText`, `s3:GetObject` (raw-addresses), `s3:PutObject` (geocoded), `kms:Decrypt`, `kms:GenerateDataKey`, CloudWatch Logs. Clustering Lambda/SageMaker: `s3:GetObject` (geocoded), `s3:PutObject` (cluster-results), `dynamodb:PutItem`, `kms:Decrypt`, `kms:GenerateDataKey`, CloudWatch Logs. Dashboard role: `dynamodb:Query`, `s3:GetObject` (cluster-results). |
[0m[49m[39m  139, 139[0m:[39m[49m | **BAA** | Required. Patient addresses are PHI. Geocoded coordinates derived from addresses are PHI. Verify Amazon Location Service appears on the [HIPAA Eligible Services list](https://aws.amazon.com/compliance/hipaa-eligible-services-reference/) before sending patient addresses. |
[0m[49m[39m  140, 140[0m:[39m[49m | **Encryption** | S3: SSE-KMS; DynamoDB: encryption at rest (default); Lambda environment variables encrypted with KMS; all transit over TLS |
[0m[49m[39m  141, 141[0m:[39m[49m | **VPC** | Production: Lambda in VPC with S3 and DynamoDB Gateway endpoints (free, no per-GB charge) and Interface endpoints for CloudWatch Logs. Location Service calls go over the public endpoint (no VPC endpoint available as of early 2026; use a NAT Gateway). Data is TLS-encrypted in transit. Document this data flow in your HIPAA risk assessment. If your compliance posture requires all PHI to remain within private network paths, consider self-hosted geocoding (Pelias on EC2 within your VPC). |
[0m[49m[39m  142, 142[0m:[39m[49m | **CloudTrail** | Enabled: log all Location Service and S3 API calls for HIPAA audit trail |
[0m[49m[39m  143, 143[0m:[39m[49m | **Sample Data** | Synthetic patient addresses. Use Census Bureau TIGER/Line files for realistic geographic distributions. Never use real patient addresses in dev. |
[0m[49m[39m  144, 144[0m:[39m[49m | **Cost Estimate** | Location Service geocoding: ~$0.50 per 1,000 requests. For 200,000 patients: ~$100 one-time, then incremental for new patients. Lambda and DynamoDB costs negligible at this scale. |
[0m[49m[39m  145, 145[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  146, 146[0m:[39m[49m ### Ingredients
[0m[49m[39m  147, 147[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  148, 148[0m:[39m[49m | AWS Service | Role |
[0m[49m[39m  149, 149[0m:[39m[49m |------------|------|
[0m[49m[39m  150, 150[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon Location Service** | Geocodes patient addresses to lat/long coordinates |
[0m[49m[39m  151, 151[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon S3** | Stores address extracts, geocoded data, and cluster results |
[0m[49m[39m  152, 152[0m:[39m[49m | **AWS Lambda** | Orchestrates geocoding batches and runs clustering for moderate datasets |
[0m[49m[39m  153, 153[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon SageMaker** | Runs clustering algorithms on large datasets (500K+ patients) |
[0m[49m[39m  154, 154[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon DynamoDB** | Stores cluster assignments and metadata for fast lookup |
[0m[49m[39m  155, 155[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon QuickSight** | Geospatial visualization of clusters and coverage gaps |
[0m[49m[39m  156, 156[0m:[39m[49m | **AWS KMS** | Manages encryption keys for all data at rest |
[0m[49m[39m  157, 157[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon CloudWatch** | Logs, metrics, and alarms for pipeline monitoring |
[0m[49m[39m  158, 158[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  159, 159[0m:[39m[49m ### Code
[0m[49m[39m  160, 160[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  161, 161[0m:[39m[49m #### Walkthrough
[0m[49m[39m  162, 162[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  163, 163[0m:[39m[49m **Step 1: Extract and prepare address data.** The pipeline starts by pulling patient addresses from your source system (EHR extract, enrollment file, claims data warehouse). The key decision here is what to include beyond the address itself. At minimum, you need a patient identifier and the full address. For enrichment later, include demographics (age, payer type) and utilization data (visit count, last visit date). This step also handles basic data quality: removing records with no address, standardizing state abbreviations, and flagging PO Boxes for special handling. Skip this step or skip the quality checks, and your geocoding step will waste API calls on addresses that can never resolve to meaningful coordinates.
[0m[49m[39m  164, 164[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  165, 165[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  166, 166[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION extract_patient_addresses(source_connection):
[0m[49m[39m  167, 167[0m:[39m[49m     // Pull patient records with geographic and demographic data.
[0m[49m[39m  168, 168[0m:[39m[49m     // We need more than just addresses: the enrichment fields make clusters actionable.
[0m[49m[39m  169, 169[0m:[39m[49m     records = query source_connection:
[0m[49m[39m  170, 170[0m:[39m[49m         SELECT patient_id, address_line_1, address_line_2, city, state, zip_code,
[0m[49m[39m  171, 171[0m:[39m[49m                date_of_birth, primary_payer, visit_count_12mo, last_visit_date
[0m[49m[39m  172, 172[0m:[39m[49m         FROM patient_demographics
[0m[49m[39m  173, 173[0m:[39m[49m         WHERE status = 'active'                    // only current patients
[0m[49m[39m  174, 174[0m:[39m[49m           AND address_line_1 IS NOT NULL           // must have an address to geocode
[0m[49m[39m  175, 175[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  176, 176[0m:[39m[49m     // Basic quality filtering before we spend money on geocoding API calls.
[0m[49m[39m  177, 177[0m:[39m[49m     cleaned = empty list
[0m[49m[39m  178, 178[0m:[39m[49m     po_box_count = 0
[0m[49m[39m  179, 179[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  180, 180[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each record in records:
[0m[49m[39m  181, 181[0m:[39m[49m         // Standardize state to two-letter abbreviation
[0m[49m[39m  182, 182[0m:[39m[49m         record.state = standardize_state(record.state)
[0m[49m[39m  183, 183[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  184, 184[0m:[39m[49m         // Flag PO Boxes: they geocode to the post office, not the patient's home.
[0m[49m[39m  185, 185[0m:[39m[49m         // We'll still geocode them (some analysis needs them), but flag for awareness.
[0m[49m[39m  186, 186[0m:[39m[49m         IF record.address_line_1 matches pattern "PO BOX" or "P.O." or "POST OFFICE":
[0m[49m[39m  187, 187[0m:[39m[49m             record.is_po_box = true
[0m[49m[39m  188, 188[0m:[39m[49m             po_box_count = po_box_count + 1
[0m[49m[39m  189, 189[0m:[39m[49m         ELSE:
[0m[49m[39m  190, 190[0m:[39m[49m             record.is_po_box = false
[0m[49m[39m  191, 191[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  192, 192[0m:[39m[49m         append record to cleaned
[0m[49m[39m  193, 193[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  194, 194[0m:[39m[49m     LOG "Extracted {length of cleaned} records. {po_box_count} PO Boxes flagged."
[0m[49m[39m  195, 195[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN cleaned
[0m[49m[39m  196, 196[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  197, 197[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  198, 198[0m:[39m[49m **Step 2: Geocode addresses to coordinates.** This is where text addresses become plottable points. The geocoding service takes a street address and returns a latitude/longitude pair with a confidence score. We process addresses in client-side batches for throughput management (controlling concurrency and rate limiting), but each address is geocoded individually. The confidence score matters because a low-confidence geocode (the service guessed at the location) can place a patient miles from their actual home, distorting your clusters. We set a threshold and route low-confidence results to a "needs review" bucket rather than silently including bad coordinates.
[0m[49m[39m  199, 199[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  200, 200[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  201, 201[0m:[39m[49m GEOCODE_CONFIDENCE_THRESHOLD = 0.85  // below this, the coordinate is too uncertain to trust
[0m[49m[39m  202, 202[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  203, 203[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION geocode_addresses(records, place_index_name):
[0m[49m[39m  204, 204[0m:[39m[49m     // Process addresses in client-side batches for rate limiting and progress tracking.
[0m[49m[39m  205, 205[0m:[39m[49m     // Amazon Location Service geocodes one address per API call (SearchPlaceIndexForText).
[0m[49m[39m  206, 206[0m:[39m[49m     // We group into batches of 50 for concurrency control, not because there's a batch API.
[0m[49m[39m  207, 207[0m:[39m[49m     geocoded = empty list
[0m[49m[39m  208, 208[0m:[39m[49m     failed = empty list
[0m[49m[39m  209, 209[0m:[39m[49m     batch_size = 50  // process this many before logging progress
[0m[49m[39m  210, 210[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  211, 211[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each batch of batch_size records:
[0m[49m[39m  212, 212[0m:[39m[49m         FOR each record in batch:
[0m[49m[39m  213, 213[0m:[39m[49m             // Build the search string from address components.
[0m[49m[39m  214, 214[0m:[39m[49m             full_address = "{record.address_line_1}, {record.city}, {record.state} {record.zip_code}"
[0m[49m[39m  215, 215[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  216, 216[0m:[39m[49m             // Call the geocoding service for this address.
[0m[49m[39m  217, 217[0m:[39m[49m             result = call LocationService.SearchPlaceIndexForText with:
[0m[49m[39m  218, 218[0m:[39m[49m                 index_name = place_index_name
[0m[49m[39m  219, 219[0m:[39m[49m                 text       = full_address
[0m[49m[39m  220, 220[0m:[39m[49m                 max_results = 1
[0m[49m[39m  221, 221[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  222, 222[0m:[39m[49m             IF result is not empty AND result.confidence >= GEOCODE_CONFIDENCE_THRESHOLD:
[0m[49m[39m  223, 223[0m:[39m[49m                 record.latitude  = result.latitude
[0m[49m[39m  224, 224[0m:[39m[49m                 record.longitude = result.longitude
[0m[49m[39m  225, 225[0m:[39m[49m                 record.geocode_confidence = result.confidence
[0m[49m[39m  226, 226[0m:[39m[49m                 append record to geocoded
[0m[49m[39m  227, 227[0m:[39m[49m             ELSE:
[0m[49m[39m  228, 228[0m:[39m[49m                 // Low confidence or no result: ambiguous address, rural route, etc.
[0m[49m[39m  229, 229[0m:[39m[49m                 record.geocode_confidence = result.confidence IF result exists ELSE 0
[0m[49m[39m  230, 230[0m:[39m[49m                 record.geocode_failure_reason = "low_confidence"
[0m[49m[39m  231, 231[0m:[39m[49m                 append record to failed
[0m[49m[39m  232, 232[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  233, 233[0m:[39m[49m         LOG "Progress: geocoded {length of geocoded} so far..."
[0m[49m[39m  234, 234[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  235, 235[0m:[39m[49m     LOG "Geocoded {length of geocoded} successfully. {length of failed} below confidence threshold."
[0m[49m[39m  236, 236[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN geocoded, failed
[0m[49m[39m  237, 237[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  238, 238[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  239, 239[0m:[39m[49m **Step 3: Clean and filter coordinates.** Even after geocoding, the data needs one more pass. Coordinates at (0, 0) mean the geocoder returned a default rather than admitting failure. Coordinates outside your service area bounding box are patients who've moved or were entered incorrectly. Duplicate coordinates (multiple patients at the same address, like a nursing home) need to be handled: you might want to count them as one point for clustering but retain the patient count for enrichment. This step ensures that what goes into the clustering algorithm is clean, bounded, and representative.
[0m[49m[39m  240, 240[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  241, 241[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  242, 242[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION clean_coordinates(geocoded_records, bounding_box):
[0m[49m[39m  243, 243[0m:[39m[49m     // bounding_box = { min_lat, max_lat, min_lon, max_lon }
[0m[49m[39m  244, 244[0m:[39m[49m     // Defines your service area. Points outside are excluded from clustering.
[0m[49m[39m  245, 245[0m:[39m[49m     cleaned = empty list
[0m[49m[39m  246, 246[0m:[39m[49m     excluded = empty list
[0m[49m[39m  247, 247[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  248, 248[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each record in geocoded_records:
[0m[49m[39m  249, 249[0m:[39m[49m         // Check for null island (0,0) which means geocoding silently failed
[0m[49m[39m  250, 250[0m:[39m[49m         IF record.latitude == 0 AND record.longitude == 0:
[0m[49m[39m  251, 251[0m:[39m[49m             record.exclusion_reason = "null_island"
[0m[49m[39m  252, 252[0m:[39m[49m             append record to excluded
[0m[49m[39m  253, 253[0m:[39m[49m             CONTINUE
[0m[49m[39m  254, 254[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  255, 255[0m:[39m[49m         // Check bounding box: is this patient within our service area?
[0m[49m[39m  256, 256[0m:[39m[49m         IF record.latitude < bounding_box.min_lat
[0m[49m[39m  257, 257[0m:[39m[49m            OR record.latitude > bounding_box.max_lat
[0m[49m[39m  258, 258[0m:[39m[49m            OR record.longitude < bounding_box.min_lon
[0m[49m[39m  259, 259[0m:[39m[49m            OR record.longitude > bounding_box.max_lon:
[0m[49m[39m  260, 260[0m:[39m[49m             record.exclusion_reason = "outside_service_area"
[0m[49m[39m  261, 261[0m:[39m[49m             append record to excluded
[0m[49m[39m  262, 262[0m:[39m[49m             CONTINUE
[0m[49m[39m  263, 263[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  264, 264[0m:[39m[49m         append record to cleaned
[0m[49m[39m  265, 265[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  266, 266[0m:[39m[49m     LOG "Retained {length of cleaned} points. Excluded {length of excluded}."
[0m[49m[39m  267, 267[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN cleaned, excluded
[0m[49m[39m  268, 268[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  269, 269[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  270, 270[0m:[39m[49m **Step 4: Run the clustering algorithm.** This is the core analytical step. We use DBSCAN because it doesn't require pre-specifying the number of clusters, handles irregular shapes, and identifies noise points (isolated patients who don't belong to any dense cluster). The two parameters to tune are epsilon (the maximum distance between two points for them to be considered neighbors) and min_samples (the minimum number of points to form a dense region). For healthcare facility planning, an epsilon of 2-5 km and min_samples of 50-200 patients is a reasonable starting range, but these depend entirely on your population density and operational question.
[0m[49m[39m  271, 271[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  272, 272[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  273, 273[0m:[39m[49m // DBSCAN parameters: these are the knobs you'll tune.
[0m[49m[39m  274, 274[0m:[39m[49m // epsilon: maximum distance (in km) between two points to be considered neighbors.
[0m[49m[39m  275, 275[0m:[39m[49m //          Smaller = tighter clusters, more noise points. Larger = looser clusters.
[0m[49m[39m  276, 276[0m:[39m[49m // min_samples: minimum points in a neighborhood to form a cluster core.
[0m[49m[39m  277, 277[0m:[39m[49m //              Higher = only dense areas form clusters. Lower = sparser areas qualify.
[0m[49m[39m  278, 278[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  279, 279[0m:[39m[49m EPSILON = 3.0        // km; roughly "within a 5-minute drive in suburban areas"
[0m[49m[39m  280, 280[0m:[39m[49m MIN_SAMPLES = 100    // at least 100 patients to form a meaningful cluster
[0m[49m[39m  281, 281[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  282, 282[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION cluster_patients(cleaned_records):
[0m[49m[39m  283, 283[0m:[39m[49m     // Extract coordinate arrays for the clustering algorithm.
[0m[49m[39m  284, 284[0m:[39m[49m     coordinates = array of [record.latitude, record.longitude] for each record in cleaned_records
[0m[49m[39m  285, 285[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  286, 286[0m:[39m[49m     // Convert epsilon from km to radians for Haversine distance metric.
[0m[49m[39m  287, 287[0m:[39m[49m     // Earth's radius is approximately 6371 km.
[0m[49m[39m  288, 288[0m:[39m[49m     epsilon_radians = EPSILON / 6371.0
[0m[49m[39m  289, 289[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  290, 290[0m:[39m[49m     // Run DBSCAN with Haversine distance (appropriate for lat/long coordinates).
[0m[49m[39m  291, 291[0m:[39m[49m     // Haversine accounts for Earth's curvature, unlike Euclidean distance which
[0m[49m[39m  292, 292[0m:[39m[49m     // would distort at higher latitudes.
[0m[49m[39m  293, 293[0m:[39m[49m     cluster_labels = DBSCAN(
[0m[49m[39m  294, 294[0m:[39m[49m         data            = coordinates,
[0m[49m[39m  295, 295[0m:[39m[49m         epsilon         = epsilon_radians,
[0m[49m[39m  296, 296[0m:[39m[49m         min_samples     = MIN_SAMPLES,
[0m[49m[39m  297, 297[0m:[39m[49m         metric          = "haversine"       // critical: use spherical distance, not flat
[0m[49m[39m  298, 298[0m:[39m[49m     )
[0m[49m[39m  299, 299[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  300, 300[0m:[39m[49m     // Assign cluster labels back to records.
[0m[49m[39m  301, 301[0m:[39m[49m     // Label -1 means "noise": the point doesn't belong to any cluster.
[0m[49m[39m  302, 302[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each record, label in zip(cleaned_records, cluster_labels):
[0m[49m[39m  303, 303[0m:[39m[49m         record.cluster_id = label
[0m[49m[39m  304, 304[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  305, 305[0m:[39m[49m     // Count results
[0m[49m[39m  306, 306[0m:[39m[49m     num_clusters = count of unique labels where label != -1
[0m[49m[39m  307, 307[0m:[39m[49m     noise_count  = count of records where cluster_id == -1
[0m[49m[39m  308, 308[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  309, 309[0m:[39m[49m     LOG "Found {num_clusters} clusters. {noise_count} noise points ({noise_count/total * 100}%)."
[0m[49m[39m  310, 310[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN cleaned_records, num_clusters
[0m[49m[39m  311, 311[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  312, 312[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  313, 313[0m:[39m[49m **Step 5: Enrich clusters with metadata.** A cluster is just a set of coordinates until you attach meaning. This step computes summary statistics for each cluster: centroid (geographic center), patient count, demographic breakdown, utilization patterns, and payer mix. These enrichments transform "there's a dense area here" into "there are 3,200 patients here, average age 58, 40% Medicare, averaging 6.2 visits per year, and the nearest existing clinic is 12 miles away." That's the information a strategy team needs to make a facility decision.
[0m[49m[39m  314, 314[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  315, 315[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  316, 316[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION enrich_clusters(clustered_records, num_clusters):
[0m[49m[39m  317, 317[0m:[39m[49m     cluster_metadata = empty map
[0m[49m[39m  318, 318[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  319, 319[0m:[39m[49m     FOR cluster_id FROM 0 TO num_clusters - 1:
[0m[49m[39m  320, 320[0m:[39m[49m         // Get all patients in this cluster
[0m[49m[39m  321, 321[0m:[39m[49m         members = filter clustered_records where record.cluster_id == cluster_id
[0m[49m[39m  322, 322[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  323, 323[0m:[39m[49m         // Compute geographic centroid (average lat/long of all members)
[0m[49m[39m  324, 324[0m:[39m[49m         centroid_lat = average of member.latitude for all members
[0m[49m[39m  325, 325[0m:[39m[49m         centroid_lon = average of member.longitude for all members
[0m[49m[39m  326, 326[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  327, 327[0m:[39m[49m         // Compute demographic summary
[0m[49m[39m  328, 328[0m:[39m[49m         avg_age = average age computed from member.date_of_birth for all members
[0m[49m[39m  329, 329[0m:[39m[49m         payer_distribution = count members grouped by member.primary_payer
[0m[49m[39m  330, 330[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  331, 331[0m:[39m[49m         // Compute utilization summary
[0m[49m[39m  332, 332[0m:[39m[49m         avg_visits_12mo = average of member.visit_count_12mo for all members
[0m[49m[39m  333, 333[0m:[39m[49m         pct_no_visit_12mo = percentage of members where visit_count_12mo == 0
[0m[49m[39m  334, 334[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  335, 335[0m:[39m[49m         // Compute geographic spread (how tight or dispersed is this cluster?)
[0m[49m[39m  336, 336[0m:[39m[49m         max_distance_from_centroid = maximum Haversine distance from centroid to any member
[0m[49m[39m  337, 337[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  338, 338[0m:[39m[49m         cluster_metadata[cluster_id] = {
[0m[49m[39m  339, 339[0m:[39m[49m             cluster_id:          cluster_id,
[0m[49m[39m  340, 340[0m:[39m[49m             patient_count:       length of members,
[0m[49m[39m  341, 341[0m:[39m[49m             centroid:            { latitude: centroid_lat, longitude: centroid_lon },
[0m[49m[39m  342, 342[0m:[39m[49m             radius_km:           max_distance_from_centroid,
[0m[49m[39m  343, 343[0m:[39m[49m             avg_age:             avg_age,
[0m[49m[39m  344, 344[0m:[39m[49m             payer_mix:           payer_distribution,
[0m[49m[39m  345, 345[0m:[39m[49m             avg_visits_12mo:     avg_visits_12mo,
[0m[49m[39m  346, 346[0m:[39m[49m             pct_disengaged:      pct_no_visit_12mo,   // patients with zero visits: potential access issue
[0m[49m[39m  347, 347[0m:[39m[49m             top_zip_codes:       top 5 ZIP codes by patient count in this cluster
[0m[49m[39m  348, 348[0m:[39m[49m         }
[0m[49m[39m  349, 349[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  350, 350[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN cluster_metadata
[0m[49m[39m  351, 351[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  352, 352[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  353, 353[0m:[39m[49m **Step 6: Store results and serve downstream.** The final step persists both the per-patient cluster assignments (so any system can look up "which cluster is this patient in?") and the cluster-level metadata (so dashboards and reports can display cluster characteristics). Writing to both a fast-lookup store (DynamoDB) and a bulk-query store (S3/Athena) covers both access patterns: real-time lookups and analytical queries.
[0m[49m[39m  354, 354[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  355, 355[0m:[39m[49m Table design: the `patient-clusters` table uses `patient_id` (string, opaque identifier) as the partition key. The `cluster-metadata` table uses `cluster_id` (number) as the partition key. No sort keys needed for point lookups. If you need "list all patients in cluster X," add a GSI on `cluster_id` to the patient-clusters table, but be aware this enables bulk enumeration of patient locations by cluster.
[0m[49m[39m  356, 356[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  357, 357[0m:[39m[49m <!-- TODO (TechWriter): Expert review SEC-3 (MEDIUM). Add S3 lifecycle policy recommendation: retain current and previous snapshot, expire older snapshots after 6-12 months. Each snapshot contains PHI; minimizing retained copies reduces exposure surface. -->
[0m[49m[39m  358, 358[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  359, 359[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  360, 360[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION store_results(clustered_records, cluster_metadata):
[0m[49m[39m  361, 361[0m:[39m[49m     // Write per-patient assignments to DynamoDB for fast point lookups.
[0m[49m[39m  362, 362[0m:[39m[49m     // Use case: "Which cluster does patient X belong to?"
[0m[49m[39m  363, 363[0m:[39m[49m     // Table: patient-clusters, partition key: patient_id (opaque, not MRN)
[0m[49m[39m  364, 364[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each record in clustered_records:
[0m[49m[39m  365, 365[0m:[39m[49m         write to DynamoDB table "patient-clusters":
[0m[49m[39m  366, 366[0m:[39m[49m             patient_id   = record.patient_id
[0m[49m[39m  367, 367[0m:[39m[49m             cluster_id   = record.cluster_id
[0m[49m[39m  368, 368[0m:[39m[49m             latitude     = record.latitude
[0m[49m[39m  369, 369[0m:[39m[49m             longitude    = record.longitude
[0m[49m[39m  370, 370[0m:[39m[49m             computed_at  = current UTC timestamp (ISO 8601)
[0m[49m[39m  371, 371[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  372, 372[0m:[39m[49m     // Write cluster metadata to DynamoDB for dashboard and API access.
[0m[49m[39m  373, 373[0m:[39m[49m     // Table: cluster-metadata, partition key: cluster_id
[0m[49m[39m  374, 374[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each cluster_id, metadata in cluster_metadata:
[0m[49m[39m  375, 375[0m:[39m[49m         write to DynamoDB table "cluster-metadata":
[0m[49m[39m  376, 376[0m:[39m[49m             cluster_id   = cluster_id
[0m[49m[39m  377, 377[0m:[39m[49m             metadata     = metadata
[0m[49m[39m  378, 378[0m:[39m[49m             computed_at  = current UTC timestamp (ISO 8601)
[0m[49m[39m  379, 379[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  380, 380[0m:[39m[49m     // Also write full results to S3 as Parquet for analytical queries via Athena.
[0m[49m[39m  381, 381[0m:[39m[49m     write clustered_records as Parquet to S3: "cluster-results/{date}/patient-assignments.parquet"
[0m[49m[39m  382, 382[0m:[39m[49m     write cluster_metadata as JSON to S3: "cluster-results/{date}/cluster-summaries.json"
[0m[49m[39m  383, 383[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  384, 384[0m:[39m[49m     LOG "Stored {length of clustered_records} patient assignments and {length of cluster_metadata} cluster summaries."
[0m[49m[39m  385, 385[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  386, 386[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  387, 387[0m:[39m[49m > **Curious how this looks in Python?** The pseudocode above covers the concepts. If you'd like to see sample Python code that demonstrates these patterns using boto3, check out the [Python Example](chapter06.01-python-example). It walks through each step with inline comments and notes on what you'd need to change for a real deployment.
[0m[49m[39m  388, 388[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  389, 389[0m:[39m[49m ### Expected Results
[0m[49m[39m  390, 390[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  391, 391[0m:[39m[49m **Sample cluster metadata output:**
